The "bea car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
Japanese society has created a robot that, for example, takes the flight of bees, can avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of the Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C is an expansion of the Security Shield of four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in vehicles in the manufacturer's home.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to Nissan's security shield.
But the most important thing is the composite eyes of bees, able to see in all directions with an angle of more than 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, engineers have developed what they have defined as a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C for a radius within two metres and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to a microprocessor on board that immediately prevents collision.
"When it detects an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at the right or greater angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and engineer head of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot divert upwards or downwards, not even diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and in the direction in which it can rotate its wheels and not exploit infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act on this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of anticipated maneuvers, so it can work without interruptions and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, not even mega."
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be serial in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the typology with lithium ions.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to destination avoiding obstacles in the path.
