The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held prisoners in the desert for ten days were brought back on Monday afternoon, safe and sound, to the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they were released in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at the military base of Almaza, near Cairo International Airport, around 15:30, on board a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were transferred immediately, without being able to issue any interviews to the press, to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They enjoy "good health" and have not been paid any ransom "to the kidnappers", said Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna on the runway.
Kidnapped on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been bombarded from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five German and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous, the organizing agency of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer said that 30 members of the special forces, on board two helicopters, had launched the attack during the night, just before dawn.
"There were gunshots, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled," said the official who requested to maintain the anonymity.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lampo" unit were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian foreign minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of secret agents and Italian special forces.
We must admit that if we have achieved this result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, the special forces," he said, without adding any further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol force claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board which the kidnappers were on and killed six, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and to have captured two.
According to the army, the kidnappers would be linked to an organization of rebels in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), a statement immediately denied by the latter.
