The fox in the cock
In America, life and health insurers, based on people's medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the poultry to the fox" - writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick the author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies shall subordinate the insurance rate and the amount to be paid in the event of health claims by the prospective customer and if they consider the risk too high they shall not specify the insurance.
A long time ago, the client had to undergo a medical visit and the contract was concluded only after the examination had taken place.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the customer's identification code you can easily have information from the pharmacies on which medicines he bought in the last year and a half and hence the evince program of which diseases he suffers and in which health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is infrequently high and is classified as the highest risk category.
There are several versions of the program on the market, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer in addition to paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
In contrast, some medicines can be used for several purposes, e.g. some compounds can be used against migraine or heat flushes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance - commercial point of view, is the risk factor, the first two nos.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed, and before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies, they ask for the patient's approval.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even though they have so far not done much for negligence.
Some companies have also recently developed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to medical consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time control of use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on privacy but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives control powers to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links the other data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
Then in the end the chickens are entrusted to the leniency of the fox.
