European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are mainly trading partners, the agenda for the ninth summit meeting was also dominated by this issue, in addition to all other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit which will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is becoming a great democratic power to which more voice should be given in international affairs, but Member States have not yet been able to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So he did not insist on this issue in the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseilles.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as President of the Union, José Manuel Barroso as Chairman of the Committee and Javier Solana as High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they found the agreement to double in five years, that is to say increase up to 100 billion euros, trade.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods has risen from 25 to 55 billion, this is not too ambitious a goal.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also take the lead in the future.
India would like to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the deal.
The aim is to balance because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only the ninth largest trading partner in the EU.
The summit devoted attention to global issues.
To the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and to terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms from both sides, and urged the convening of a UN conference.
They called for the conclusion of the Doha Round, although both sides had a role to play in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed that the energy and climate programme will continue, i.e. it would like to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as on the need to conclude a global pact at next year's climate conference and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb the increase in food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
Today, the Indian Prime Minister will visit the French capital where a bilateral meeting is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris it is hoped that to build the Indian nuclear reactors the French companies will receive a commitment worth 20 billion euros.
